{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015t9x8YSaThhLbxy1rds3qB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. In `precall_c`:\n\n1. A new CI is pushed (`prep_call_info`)\n2. The C function `f` is called: `let n = f(state)? as i32`\n3. `poscall(state, ci_idx, n)?` is called to handle return\n\nWhen `f(state)?` runs:\n- `f` is `aux_wrap`\n- Inside `aux_wrap`, `state.call(nargs, -1)` is called → this is an unprotected call\n- If the wrapped function errors, `state.call(nargs, -1)` returns `Err(e)`\n\n\n- The result isn't immediately propagated with `?`, it's stored in `call_result` and matched on, so `aux_wrap` handles the error itself. But here's the issue: after `state.call(nargs, -1)` fails, `state.ci` is still pointing to the inner function's call info, not the wrapper's.\n\nLooking at how `precall_c` manages this, it sets up a new call info frame before invoking the C function, then uses `poscall` to restore the previous frame afterward—so even if the inner call errors, the restoration should happen when `poscall` is called.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1737,"cache_read_input_tokens":158300,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1737},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7b02f0cd-a42a-42b3-ada8-8c5d45862757","uuid":"f71b0898-2a0c-459a-92c2-7d6a11ab7bd7","request_id":"req_011CbBBwL7tmKdWjS5FySfJa"}
